        <h2>An Adventure on the Palate from History to Today</h2>
        <br>
        <img class="main-img" src="./img/history1.png" alt="Italian Food Timeline">
        <br>
        <div class="content">
          <p>Italian cuisine represents a culinary adventure that has been embraced and appreciated by a huge fan base around the world for centuries. After the fall of the Roman Empire, the different regions of Italy developed their own traditions, which continue to this day throughout the country. Perhaps the most distinctive feature of Italian cuisine lies in its simplicity. Most dishes are made with only a few ingredients, which is why Italian chefs often emphasize the quality of the ingredients rather than the complexity of the preparation process.</p>
          <p>Throughout history, Italian cuisine has undergone many transformations and spread all over the world. Especially with the discovery of the American continent and the introduction of products from the New World such as potatoes, tomatoes, peppers, corn and sugar beets. These added new flavors and richness to Italian cuisine. However, most Italian dishes are still rooted in the past and retain their traditional flavors.</p>
          <p>Regional diversity is also an important feature of Italian cuisine. From the north to the south of the country, different regions have their own unique recipes and food cultures. For example, risotto and tortellini are popular in northern Italy, while in the south Naples is known for its famous pizzas. Each region has its own recipes and ingredients, making Italian cuisine versatile and rich.</p>
          <p>One of the pillars of Italian cuisine is the Mediterranean diet, a healthy and nutritious diet. Enriched with pasta, fish, fruits and vegetables, this diet explains why Italian cuisine is so popular for health and taste. Cheese, charcuterie and wine are also at the heart of Italian cuisine and are an integral part of Italian gastronomic culture, along with iconic flavors such as pizza and coffee.</p>
          <img class="add-img" src="./img/history2.png" alt="Italian Food">
          <p>When we look at the history of Italian cuisine, we see that it has been developing since Ancient Rome. The first known food writer who had a great influence on Italian cuisine was Archestratus, a Greek who lived in the 4th century BC. Even then, there was an emphasis on using quality and seasonal ingredients. However, with the rise of the Roman Empire, the food culture became more complex and many different dishes and cooking techniques were developed.</p>
          <p>During the Middle Ages, Italian cuisine came under Arab influence. The Arabs invaded Sicily and introduced new flavors to Italian cuisine, such as spinach, almonds and rice. The Arabs also introduced new ingredients to Italian cuisine, which today form the basis of traditional Italian dishes. During the Middle Ages, food preservation methods were also developed and meat, fish and vegetables were preserved by salting, drying and smoking.</p>
          <p>At the beginning of the New Age, Italian cuisine became richer and more varied. In the 18th century, Italian cookbooks emphasized the superiority of regional Italian cuisine over French cuisine. During this period, new world ingredients such as tomatoes, beans, pumpkins, squash and peppers were added to Italian cuisine. These ingredients further enriched Italian cuisine and even today form the basis of many classic Italian dishes.</p>
          <p>In the modern era, Italian cuisine has made a huge impact around the world and has won many international awards. In particular, with the popularization of Italian food in English, Italian cuisine has spread worldwide and become a much-loved cuisine. Today, Italian cuisine has become a worldwide phenomenon, not only because of its simple and delicious recipes, but also because Italian food culture is unique and attractive.</p>
